1 hour ago, ra4nd0m said:

How exactly compares bdb tanks with the same tanks from vanilla (restock) such as titan tanks? Is there any huge differences other then texture?

They should be roughly similar and mass fractions should be similar too (except balloon tanks which are much lighter for an equivalent size). But our tanks are not strictly balanced based on matching the volume of stock tanks rather its based on 20% of real world fuel mass so the fuel density can vary. Fuel density is not consistent in stock either though.

Is the current  version of  BDB compatible with Skyhawk science system, or does it need any manual tweaks?

Are contracts provided by BDB comprehensive enough, and/or are there any other contract packs required/recommended for a good BDB career experience? (Also, general recommendations on probes and planetary-oriented contract packs will be greatly appreciated)

22 minutes ago, Alpha512 said:

Are contracts provided by BDB comprehensive enough, and/or are there any other contract packs required/recommended for a good BDB career experience? (Also, general recommendations on probes and planetary-oriented contract packs will be greatly appreciated)

I've only used BDB on sandbox saves before, hence the need for some help

Skyhawk is pretty good, though recent things like Voyager Mars aren't configured properly. As for contracts, I'm not really sure I've seen any set of contracts that provides a particularly good career experience without completely overhauling contracts (which RP-1 does), but I don't think there's anything wrong with BDB ones. I'd recommend Strategia though, since although it's not a contract pack it gives you incentives to explore and to otherwise play in interesting ways.

Speaking of Skyhawk's techtree I finally did a Mun landing with it.

Mission: Apollo 4.

Payload: CSM named Amadeus and LEM named Falco.

Crew: Valentina as Commander and LM pilot, Jebediah as CSM pilot and Bill as Engineer.

Unfortunately Falco's name decal did not load.

CTV camera footage of Valentina steeping onto the surface.

Now Bill, thanks Val for holding the camera.

Thankfully I did not unlock the ALSEP because  where I landed parallax lagged my computer to no end.

Meet my latest creation/abomination: 

What if NASA decided to use Orion on the ISS... and chose Atlas V as its launch vehicle.

This abomination is Atlas V N2D2 where D2 is DCSS with 2 RL10 B2s 

It flies suprisingly well.

And looks pretty good escpecially considering the existance of the Ares I

50% Saturn 50% SLS
